                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true" xml:id="binding">
                              <p>The cover has been removed carelessly, probably to have acces to the sewing and repair it.
                                However, most of the binding (the remains of the cover and the boards) is likely contemporary to the manuscript content.</p>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                The book is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards, once fully covered with brown blind-tooled <material
                                key="leather">leather</material>.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                The boards are cut to the same size as the bookblock. The grain runs vertically.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Cover" color="brown">
                                Full brown blind-tooled leather cover. The turn-ins have been trimmed out and they form butt mitres at the corners.
                                <term key="additionalLeatherPatch">Additional leather patches</term> had been added along the inner margin of the boards
                                to fill the gap between the turn-ins, but later they have been removed probably to access the sewing and repair it.
                                Only the turn-ins and part of the lower cover have been preserved. The lower cover shows a fine blind-tooled decoration.
                                The turn-ins and the spine are also decorated.
                                The decoration consists of five concentric frames surrounding a central rectangular panel featuring a Latin cross.
                                Frames composed by the repetition of single tools, enclosed between <term key="doubleStraightLine">double straight lines</term>,
                                alternate with empty ones.
                                Proceeding from the outer to the inner frame, the repeating decoration motifs are <term key="crissCross">criss-crosses</term> (in two variants) and
                                <term key="straightStrapwork">straight strapwork</term> elements.
                                A third variant of criss-cross motifs between double straight lines forms the cross.
                                At the ends of the arms of the cross there are pairs of <term key="crescent">crescents</term> disposed to resemble a corniform motif,
                                and three <term key="doubleCircle">double circles</term>. Dotted lines surmonted by a double circle intersect at the centre of the cross forming a <foreign xml:lang="la">crux decussata</foreign>.
                                At the foot of the cross, the same criss-cross motif used in the first frame functions as a pedestal surrounded by five double circles.
                                Concentric frames of double straight lines decorate the turn-ins.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Endbands">
                                The endbands are missing, but their turn-ins have been preserved.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b6">
                               Chainstitch sewing on four sewing stations (two pairs); periodic fold pattern; Z-plied threads.
                               Between each pair of sewing stations there are two thread lengths, except in the first quire where there is one length.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b7" type="Spine">
                                At the head and tail are preserved the short horizontal stitches used to pierce the leather on the spine
                                (at the head and tail), thus fixing the endbands to the cover. Two sets of holes are visible close to the head: at c.10 mm and
                                c.25 mm from the head. Another set is visible at c.10 mm from the tail.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b8" type="SlipCase">
                                According to the auction catalogue (Sotheby's), the manuscript was sold in a leather slip case.
                                The manuscript, however, is currently not kept in a book case.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Other">
                                Coloured <term key="leafTabMark">leaf tab markers</term> are inserted in the outer margin of
                                folia with the incipit page of the days on <locus target="#19 #45 #65 #109"/>. The threads for Friday (<locus
                                target="#90"/>) and Sunday (<locus target="#123"/>) are
                                probably lost (a hole is visible on each of those folia). A
                                loose piece of red textile is kept on <locus target="#20r"/>.
                              </decoNote>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate from="1650" to="1750" evidence="lettering"> </origDate> The
                            date of production, taking into account the handwriting and the frame on <locus target="#4r"/>,
                            is probably a period between the mid-seventeenth to mid-eighteenth century. The name of <persName
                                ref="PRS12973Rehr">Rǝḫruḫ Krǝstos</persName> is mentioned in the
                            supplication formulas throughout the manuscript following the phrase
                            <foreign xml:lang="gez">ገበርከ፡</foreign> ‘your servant’. This person
                            was either the patron, the owner, the donor or the scribe of the
                            manuscript. </origin>
                        <provenance> Bought by <persName ref="PRS5782JuelJen"/> at Sotheby's
